If you want to be really fancy, there are drill bits designed to do this but really, any electric drill should do the job. The size of the holes is up to you––you can enlarge them by using a "carving" action with the drill as you make the initial hole and simply working at it until the hole is large enough. The best look will come from trying to keep the holes the same shape all the way around. But don't despair if a few are lopsided––it'll still work. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a3/Carve-a-Disco-Ball-Pumpkin-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Carve-a-Disco-Ball-Pumpkin-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a3/Carve-a-Disco-Ball-Pumpkin-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Carve-a-Disco-Ball-Pumpkin-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
